SIMPLE: gripe
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Gripe
<hw>Gripe</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See
<er>Grype</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A vulture; the
griffin.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Like a white hind under the <qex>gripe's</qex> sharp claws.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Gripe's egg</b></col>, <cd>an alchemist's vessel.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>E. Jonson.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gripe</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Gripe
<hw>Gripe</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Griped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Griping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>gripan</ets>; akin to
D. <ets>grijpen</ets>, G. <ets>greifen</ets>, OHG. <ets>gr<?/fan</ets>,
Icel. <ets>gripa</ets>, Sw. <ets>gripe</ets>, Dan. <ets>gribe</ets>,
Goth. <ets>greipan</ets>; cf. Lith. <ets>graibyti</ets>, Russ.
<ets>grabite</ets> to plunder, Skr. <ets>grah</ets>, <ets>grabh</ets>,
to seize. Cf. <er>Grip</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>,
<er>Grope</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To catch with the hand; to clasp closely with the
fingers; to clutch.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To seize and hold fast; to embrace
closely.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wouldst thou <qex>gripe</qex> both gain and pleasure ?</q>
<rj><qau>Robynson (More's Utopia).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To pinch; to distress. Specifically, to cause
pinching and spasmodic pain to the bowels of, as by the effects of
certain purgative or indigestible substances.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How inly sorrow <qex>gripes</qex> his soul.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gripe</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Gripe
<hw>Gripe</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To clutch, hold, or
pinch a thing, esp. money, with a gripe or as with a gripe.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To suffer griping pains.</def>
<rj><au>Jocke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To tend to come up into the wind,
as a ship which, when sailing closehauled, requires constant labor at
the helm.</def> <rj><au>R. H. Dana, Jr.</au></rj></p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>to complain</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gripe</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Gripe
<hw>Gripe</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Grasp; seizure; fast
hold; clutch.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A barren scepter in my <qex>gripe</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That on which the grasp is put; a handle; a grip;
<as>as, the <ex>gripe</ex> of a sword</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>A device for grasping or holding
anything; a brake to stop a wheel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Oppression; cruel exaction; affiction; pinching
distress; <as>as, the gripe of poverty</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Pinching and spasmodic pain in the intestines; --
chiefly used in the plural.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The piece of timber
which terminates the keel at the fore end; the forefoot.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>The compass or sharpness of a ship's stern under the
water, having a tendency to make her keep a good wind.</def>
<sd>(c)</sd> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>An assemblage of ropes, dead-eyes,
and hocks, fastened to ringbolts in the deck, to secure the boats when
hoisted; also, broad bands passed around a boat to secure it at the
davits and prevent swinging.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Gripe penny</b></col>,
<col><b>a</b></col></mcol><cd> miser; a niggard<-- ; a pinchpenny?
-->.</cd> <rj><au>D. L. Mackenzie.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gripeful</ent>⟦br⟧
